s) of the words and terms are calculated and used.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> The scentences in the converted textfiles are being recognised (komma, full stop, semicolon, etc). All the words are being identified and compared with the linguistical database (2.7 Mio entries). If necessary there is also a lexical analysis for the endings (i.e. "es" "'s", etc.). At the same time InfoCodex is doing a CWR ("Collocated Word Recognition") and checks if several words form a term or not. Example: The Term "European Court of Justice" is being recognised as one term not as "European", "Court", "of", "Justice".%0a> %0a> During the Text Mining Phase for all the words and terms the part of speech (name, noun, word, etc.), the significance, the language, the synonymgroup, and the link pointing to the Ontology tree are grabed out of the linguistical database and noted for late usage. At the same time the language recognition is done for the text block.%0a> %0a> !! Step 3: Construction of the 100-dimensional Contentspace%0a> The accumulated frequencies with witch the texts out of all the documents are pointing to the knots in the ontology tree result in an image of topical relevancy (main topics) in the document collection. With a Cluster-Analysis InfoCodex creates a 100-dimensional Contentspace that reproduces the content of the documents available in the best possible manner. Thereby also the Entropies (Uncertancies) of the words and terms are calculated and used.%0a> %0a15,16c15,16%0a%3c All the information collected in step 2, including the collected entropies are being used to project every single text document of step 3 into Content space%0a%3c %0a---%0a> All the information collected in step 2, including the collected entropies are being used to project every single text document of step 3 into Contentspace.%0a> %0a18,19c18,19%0a%3c The vectors form the input for the self-organizing neural network ([[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kohonen | Kohonen Map]]). This model now organizes the log